Password Reset Poisoning via Middleware

Overview

This lab demonstrates a Password Reset Poisoning vulnerability caused by improper trust in proxy-related HTTP headers.

The application generates password reset links using user-controlled header values. By manipulating these headers, an attacker can force the application to create password reset URLs pointing to an attacker-controlled domain.

When the victim clicks the poisoned reset link, the password reset token is leaked to the attacker, resulting in account takeover.

This vulnerability is a combination of Host Header Injection and Broken Authentication.

---

Vulnerability Description

Applications commonly generate password reset links using the hostname contained in incoming HTTP requests.

A secure implementation should only use trusted server-side configuration values when generating security-sensitive URLs.

If an application trusts proxy-related headers such as:

X-Forwarded-Host

an attacker may inject a malicious domain into password reset emails.

As a result, password reset tokens can be redirected to attacker-controlled infrastructure.

---

Lab Objective

Obtain Carlos's password reset token and gain access to his account.

---

Steps Performed

1. Analyze Password Reset Functionality

Logged into the application using the provided credentials and navigated to the password reset functionality.

Observed that password reset requests generated email-based recovery links.

---

2. Intercept Password Reset Request

Using Burp Suite, intercepted the password reset request.

Example:

POST /forgot-password HTTP/1.1

username=carlos

---

3. Inject a Malicious Host Header

Modified the request by adding an attacker-controlled host value.

Example:

X-Forwarded-Host: exploit-server.attacker.net

The application trusted this header when generating password reset URLs.

---

4. Trigger Password Reset Email

Submitted a password reset request for Carlos's account.

The application generated a reset email containing a link that referenced the attacker-controlled domain.

---

5. Capture Password Reset Token

When Carlos clicked the password reset link, the request was sent to the attacker's exploit server.

The password reset token appeared within the exploit server access logs.

Example:

GET /reset?temp-forgot-password-token=<token>

---

6. Reset Carlos's Password

Extracted the captured token and used it within the legitimate password reset workflow.

Assigned a new password to Carlos's account.

---

7. Access Carlos's Account

Authenticated using Carlos's username and the newly configured password.

The lab was marked as solved.

---

Attack Flow

Attacker requests password reset
            ↓
Application generates reset URL
            ↓
Application trusts X-Forwarded-Host
            ↓
Attacker injects malicious domain
            ↓
Victim receives poisoned email
            ↓
Victim clicks reset link
            ↓
Token sent to attacker server
            ↓
Attacker captures token
            ↓
Password reset performed
            ↓
Account Takeover

---

Impact

If exploited in a real-world application, attackers may:

- Capture password reset tokens
- Reset victim passwords
- Gain unauthorized account access
- Bypass authentication controls
- Compromise privileged accounts
- Achieve complete account takeover

---

Root Cause

The application trusted user-controlled proxy headers when generating password reset URLs.

Security-sensitive links were constructed using untrusted input rather than trusted server-side configuration.

---

Mitigation

Recommended Security Measures

- Use fixed server-side hostnames for password reset URLs
- Do not trust user-controlled Host or X-Forwarded-Host headers
- Validate proxy headers through trusted reverse proxies only
- Implement token expiration and one-time usage
- Monitor suspicious password reset activity
- Apply additional verification for sensitive accounts

